From eb4f744820832aff3d6da1bba14f12e91a5b3535 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Marian Csontos <mcsontos@redhat.com>
Date: Wed, 19 Feb 2025 12:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] udev: persist DM device state across initrd switch-root

Without OPTIONS+="db_persist", the udev database entries for device-mapper
devices (including LUKS/cryptsetup) are wiped when udev cleans up on
switch-root. This causes device symlinks (/dev/disk/by-uuid/, by-partuuid/)
to disappear, and systemd cannot find the root device, triggering a
dracut-initqueue timeout and emergency shell.

This is the fix from upstream LVM2 commit eb4f744 which landed in 2.03.24.

Upstream: https://github.com/lvmteam/lvm2/commit/eb4f744820832aff3d6da1bba14f12e91a5b3535
---
 udev/10-dm.rules.in | 5 +++++
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+)

diff --git a/udev/10-dm.rules.in b/udev/10-dm.rules.in
--- a/udev/10-dm.rules.in
+++ b/udev/10-dm.rules.in
@@ -44,6 +44,11 @@ KERNEL!="dm-[0-9]*", GOTO="dm_end"
 # is not recommended.
 ACTION!="add|change", GOTO="dm_end"
 
+# Persist device state on transition from the initrd. This means all udev device
+# properties are kept in the udev database even when it is cleaned up on
+# switch-root.
+OPTIONS+="db_persist"
+
 # Decode udev control flags and set environment variables appropriately.
 # These flags are encoded in DM_COOKIE variable that was introduced in
 # kernel version 2.6.31. Therefore, we can use this feature with
